Reasoning: The claim states that homozygous deletion of the murine Sbds gene from osterix-expressing mesenchymal stem and progenitor cells (MPCs) prevents oxidative stress. However, evidence from paper 3863543, "Mesenchymal Inflammation Drives Genotoxic Stress in Hematopoietic Stem Cells and Predicts Disease Evolution in Human Pre-leukemia," directly refutes this. Proposition 1 (prop_1578) and Proposition 6 (prop_1577) from this paper explicitly state that "Perturbation of mesenchymal cells in a mouse model of Shwachman-Diamond syndrome induces oxidative stress" and "Perturbation of mesenchymal cells in a mouse model of Shwachman-Diamond syndrome induces mitochondrial dysfunction," respectively. The abstract of paper 3863543 further confirms that "perturbation of mesenchymal cells in a mouse model of the pre-leukemic disorder Shwachman-Diamond syndrome (SDS) induces mitochondrial dysfunction, oxidative stress, and activation of DNA damage responses in hematopoietic stem and progenitor cells." Shwachman-Diamond syndrome is caused by mutations in the Sbds gene. Therefore, the perturbation of mesenchymal cells in an SDS mouse model, which is linked to the Sbds gene, leads to oxidative stress, directly contradicting the claim that its deletion *prevents* oxidative stress.
